# [HACKATHON](../wg/hackathon.html)

## Summary

The IETF 126 Hackathon session featured rapid-fire progress reports from various development teams. Because of scheduling constraints, presenters summarized their achievements in brief 60-to-90-second sessions. The projects spanned a wide range of IETF technologies, including security and attestation, post-quantum cryptography, routing and validation, network management, and AI-driven networking. Key efforts focused on validating draft specifications, building open-source implementations, and executing interoperability testing.

---

## Key Discussion Points

### Featured Presentations

*   **[MUD extensions and clarifications](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-hackathon-sessa-mud-extensions-and-clarifications-00)**
    *   Presented by **Elliot**.
    *   The team focused on Manufacturer Usage Descriptions (MUD) (RFC 8520) and Tunnel Extensible Authentication Protocol (TEAP) changes.
    *   For MUD, they explored extensions to clarify the use of IP addresses in MUD files, local segment multicast requirements, and directed broadcasts.
    *   They implemented a drag-and-drop PCAP-to-MUD file generation tool on MUD Maker. 
    *   A bug was identified in the current specification, which will be addressed with the working group.

*   **[Validate YANG-Push to Message Broker End-To-End Data Processing Chain](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-hackathon-sessa-validate-yang-push-to-message-broker-end-to-end-data-processing-chain-00)**
    *   Presented by **Speaker 68**.
    *   The project successfully tested end-to-end interoperability between a YANG-Push publisher/receiver and a message broker producer/consumer in a schema registry.
    *   The testing verified DTLS and CBOR recording, evaluated RPCs from system capabilities, and compared different network operating system implementations using emerging IETF and IEEE YANG models.

*   **[DRIP End-To-End Implementation with DNS](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-hackathon-sessa-drip-end-to-end-implementation-with-dns-00)**
    *   Presented by **Speaker 42**.
    *   The team demonstrated an end-to-end implementation compliant with DRIP specifications (RFC 9374 and RFC 9886).
    *   The experimental setup featured a live DNS server, a drone emulator running on a Nordic Semiconductor board, and an observer application on an Android smartphone to validate drone identification, broadcast messages, and HDA endorsements.

*   **[vCon](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-hackathon-sessa-vcon-00)**
    *   Presented by **Dan Petrie**.
    *   The team updated the vCon core specification based on recent draft changes.
    *   They engaged in a CDDL (Concise Data Definition Language) schema analysis to resolve ambiguities in the text, which will be integrated into the next draft release.

